<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,692,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1448,1475]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[345,529,1449,1475]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berela">
<emphasis box="[345,529,1449,1475]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Apenesia berela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is promptly recognized by having the body reddish-brown since other species are usually dark brown or black. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[536,720,1485,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berela">
<emphasis box="[536,720,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Apenesia berela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[779,909,1485,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amenula">
<emphasis box="[779,909,1485,1511]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. amenula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have the aedeagus dorsal lobe long, which is unusual within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1874" box="[326,429,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[326,429,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Apenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species. However, despite the body color, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[913,1016,1521,1547]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berela">
<emphasis box="[913,1016,1521,1547]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. berela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mandible with one tooth; the metapostnotal median carina absent and the hypopygium flap and posterior margin concave, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Alencar &amp; Azevedo" authorityYear="2020" box="[1307,1436,1557,1583]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amenula">
<emphasis box="[1307,1436,1557,1583]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">A. amenula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the mandible with five teeth; the metapostnotal median carina present and the hypopygium without a flap and the posterior margin almost straight.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
